dataframes = []
In [ ]:
pattern = r"output of log_reg model_batch(\d+)_epochs(\d+)_lr([\d.]+)_optimizer(.+)\.pickle"
check = 0
for file in os.listdir(directory):
    match = re.match(pattern, file)
    if match:
        filepath = os.path.join(directory, file)
        df = pd.read_pickle(filepath)
        # Extract values using groups from regex match
        batch_size, epochs, learning_rate, optimizer = match.groups()
        # Convert extracted values to the appropriate data types
        batch_size = int(batch_size)
        epochs = int(epochs)
        learning_rate = float(learning_rate)
        # Add extracted values to the DataFrame explicitly
        df['Batch_Size'] = batch_size
        df['Epochs'] = epochs
        df['Learning_Rate'] = learning_rate
        df['Optimizer'] = optimizer
        # Append the DataFrame to the list
        if batch_size == 1:
            continue
        dataframes.append(df)

# Define the metrics and hyperparameters
metrics = ['Time','Accuracy', 'Precision', 'Recall', 'F1 score']
hyperparameters = ['Learning_Rate','Batch_Size', 'Epochs', 'Optimizer']

# Generate combinations of metrics and pairs of hyperparameters
combinations = list(itertools.product(metrics, itertools.combinations(hyperparameters, 2)))

# Set style for the plots
sns.set(style="whitegrid")

# Create subplots for each metric
for metric in metrics:
    # Filter combinations for the current metric
    metric_combinations = [(x_axis_param, hue_param) for (m, (x_axis_param, hue_param)) in combinations if m == metric]
    
    if not metric_combinations:
        continue  # Skip if no combinations for the current metric
    
    num_plots = len(metric_combinations)
    num_rows = (num_plots - 1) // 2 + 1  # Calculate the number of rows for subplots
    
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(num_rows, 2, figsize=(12, num_rows * 5))
    axes = axes.flatten()
    
    for i, (x_axis_param, hue_param) in enumerate(metric_combinations):
        # Skip if the same parameter is repeated (e.g., ('Batch_Size', 'Batch_Size'))
        if x_axis_param == hue_param:
            continue
        
        grouped_data = combined_df.groupby([x_axis_param, hue_param])[metric].mean().reset_index()
        
        if len(grouped_data) == 0:
            continue
        
        plt.sca(axes[i])
        
        # Scatter plot with lines connecting points of the same hue value
        sns.scatterplot(data=grouped_data, x=x_axis_param, y=metric, hue=hue_param, marker='o', s=100)
        for val in grouped_data[hue_param].unique():
            subset = grouped_data[grouped_data[hue_param] == val]
            plt.plot(subset[x_axis_param], subset[metric], marker='o', markersize=8)
        
        # Set x-axis to logarithmic scale if Learning Rate
        if x_axis_param == 'Learning_Rate':
            plt.xscale('log')
            plt.xticks([0.0001, 0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1], labels=['0.0001', '0.001', '0.01', '0.1', '1'])
        
        plt.title(f'{metric} vs. {x_axis_param} with {hue_param} differentiation')
        plt.xlabel(x_axis_param)
        plt.ylabel(metric)
        plt.legend(loc='best')
    
    for j in range(i + 1, len(axes)):
        axes[j].axis('off')  # Disable remaining empty subplots
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

optimizers_values = ['SGD', 'Adam']

# Load models and extract information from filenames
data_frames = []
In [ ]:
for epochs in epochs_values:
    for learning_rate in learning_rates_values:
        for optimizer_name in optimizers_values:
            # Filepaths for loading models
            filepath1 = f"C:/Users/rjuya/OneDrive/Desktop/github stuff/EE5610/Project/Models/DeitTune/outputdietmodel_epochs{epochs}_lr{learning_rate}_optimizer{optimizer_name}.pickle"
            filepath2 = f"C:/Users/rjuya/OneDrive/Desktop/github stuff/EE5610/Project/Models/DeitTune/outputdietmodelCustomMean_epochs{epochs}_lr{learning_rate}_optimizer{optimizer_name}.pickle"
            
            # Load models from the filepaths and extract information
            for filepath in [filepath1, filepath2]:
                with open(filepath, 'rb') as f:
                    # Load the model data from the pickle file
                    model_data = pickle.load(f)

                    # Extract information from the filename to determine 'Mean' value
                    mean_type = 'Default' if 'CustomMean' not in filepath else 'Custom'

                    # Add columns to the model_data DataFrame
                    model_data['Epochs'] = epochs
                    model_data['Learning_Rate'] = learning_rate
                    model_data['Optimizer'] = optimizer_name
                    model_data['Mean'] = mean_type
                    
                    # Append the DataFrame to the list
                    data_frames.append(model_data)

# Define the metrics and hyperparameters
metrics = ['Time','Accuracy', 'Precision', 'Recall', 'F1 score']
hyperparameters = ['Learning_Rate','Epochs', 'Optimizer', 'Mean']

# Generate combinations of metrics and pairs of hyperparameters
combinations = list(itertools.product(metrics, itertools.combinations(hyperparameters, 2)))

# Set style for the plots
sns.set(style="whitegrid")

# Create subplots for each metric
for metric in metrics:
    # Filter combinations for the current metric
    metric_combinations = [(x_axis_param, hue_param) for (m, (x_axis_param, hue_param)) in combinations if m == metric]
    
    if not metric_combinations:
        continue  # Skip if no combinations for the current metric
    
    num_plots = len(metric_combinations)
    num_rows = (num_plots - 1) // 2 + 1  # Calculate the number of rows for subplots
    
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(num_rows, 2, figsize=(12, num_rows * 5))
    axes = axes.flatten()
    
    for i, (x_axis_param, hue_param) in enumerate(metric_combinations):
        # Skip if the same parameter is repeated (e.g., ('Batch_Size', 'Batch_Size'))
        if x_axis_param == hue_param:
            continue
        
        grouped_data = combined_models_df.groupby([x_axis_param, hue_param])[metric].mean().reset_index()
        
        if len(grouped_data) == 0:
            continue
        
        plt.sca(axes[i])
        
        # Scatter plot with lines connecting points of the same hue value
        sns.scatterplot(data=grouped_data, x=x_axis_param, y=metric, hue=hue_param, marker='o', s=100)
        for val in grouped_data[hue_param].unique():
            subset = grouped_data[grouped_data[hue_param] == val]
            plt.plot(subset[x_axis_param], subset[metric], marker='o', markersize=8)
        
        # Set x-axis to logarithmic scale if Learning Rate
        if x_axis_param == 'Learning_Rate':
            plt.xscale('log')
            plt.xticks([0.0001, 0.001, 0.01], labels=['0.0001', '0.001', '0.01'])
        
        plt.title(f'{metric} vs. {x_axis_param} with {hue_param} differentiation')
        plt.xlabel(x_axis_param)
        plt.ylabel(metric)
        plt.legend(loc='best')
    
    for j in range(i + 1, len(axes)):
        axes[j].axis('off')  # Disable remaining empty subplots
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Create a copy of the combined_models_df DataFrame
copied_df = combined_models_df.copy()

# Define the metrics
metrics = ['Accuracy', 'Precision', 'Recall', 'F1 score']

# Iterate through each metric
for metric in metrics:
    # Sort the DataFrame based on the metric
    sorted_metric = copied_df.sort_values(by=metric, ascending=False)
    
    # Create a column containing rank of the metric
    sorted_metric[f'rank_{metric.replace(" ", "_")}'] = sorted_metric.reset_index().index + 1
    
    # # Calculate the mean of the ranks
    # mean_rank = sorted_metric[f'rank_{metric.replace(" ", "_")}'].mean()
    
    # # Add mean rank column to the copied_df
    # copied_df[f'mean_rank_{metric.replace(" ", "_")}'] = mean_rank
    
    # Add individual ranks to the copied_df
    copied_df = pd.merge(copied_df, sorted_metric[[f'rank_{metric.replace(" ", "_")}']], left_index=True, right_index=True)

# Calculate the mean of rank_MetricName columns and add a new column for the mean rank
rank_columns = [f'rank_{metric.replace(" ", "_")}' for metric in metrics]
copied_df['mean_rank_all_metrics'] = copied_df[rank_columns].mean(axis=1)

# Sort the DataFrame based on the 'mean_rank_all_metrics' column
copied_df = copied_df.sort_values(by='mean_rank_all_metrics', ascending=True)

# Display the sorted DataFrame
copied_df.head()

# Load data frames from pickle files and assign row names
data_frames = []
for filepath in filepaths:
    with open(filepath, 'rb') as f:
        # Load the dataframe from the pickle file
        df = pickle.load(f)
        
        # Assign row name based on the filename (excluding the file extension)
        row_name = filepath.split('/')[-1].split('.')[0]  # Modify as per your file structure
        df.index = [row_name] * len(df)  # Assign the row name to all rows
        
        # Append the dataframe to the list
        data_frames.append(df)

# Combine all data frames into a single dataframe
combined_df = pd.concat(data_frames)
display(combined_df.sort_values(by='F1 score', ascending=False))

# Load data frames from pickle files and assign row names
data_frames = []
for filepath in filepaths:
    with open(filepath, 'rb') as f:
        # Load the dataframe from the pickle file
        df = pickle.load(f)
        
        # Assign row name based on the filename (excluding the file extension)
        row_name = filepath.split('/')[-1].split('.')[0]  # Modify as per your file structure
        df.index = [row_name] * len(df)  # Assign the row name to all rows
        
        # Append the dataframe to the list
        data_frames.append(df)

# Combine all data frames into a single dataframe
combined_df = pd.concat(data_frames)
display(combined_df.sort_values(by='Accuracy', ascending=False))

# Load data frames from pickle files and assign row names
data_frames = []
count = 1
for filepath in filepaths:
    with open(filepath, 'rb') as f:
        # Load the dataframe from the pickle file
        df = pickle.load(f)
        
        # Assign row name based on the filename (excluding the file extension)
        row_name = filepath.split('/')[-1].split('.')[0]  # Modify as per your file structure
        df.index = [row_name] * len(df)  # Assign the row name to all rows
        if count == 1:
            count+=1
            df['Layers'] = [3,4,5,6,7]
            df['% trained'] = [100,100,100/16,100/16,100/16]
        else:
            df['Layers'] = [2]
            df['% trained'] = [100/16]
        # Append the dataframe to the list
        data_frames.append(df)

# Combine all data frames into a single dataframe
combined_df = pd.concat(data_frames)
display(combined_df.sort_values(by='Accuracy', ascending=False))
